d the Postmodernist Elegy, Greenwood Press, 1999.</P><P><FONT COLOR="#660000">&#183;</FONT>&nbsp;Helen Benedict. "Flight from Predictability: Joseph Brodsky," The Antioch Review, Winter 1985, vol. 42 (1), pp. 9-21.</P><P><FONT COLOR="#660000">&#183;</FONT>&nbsp;Peter Forbes. "Joseph Brodsky: The Acceleration of a Poet," Poetry Review, Spring 1988, vol. 78 (1), pp. 4-5.</P><P><FONT COLOR="#660000">&#183;</FONT>&nbsp;Anna Tavis. "A Journey from Petersburg to Stockholm: Preliminary Biography of Joseph Brodsky," Slavic Review, Fall 1988, vol. 47 (3), pp. 499-501.</P><P><FONT COLOR="#660000">&#183;</FONT>&nbsp;Galya Diment. "'Tolstoy or Dostoevsky' and the Modernists: Polemics with Joseph Brodsky," Tolstoy Studies Journal, 1990, vol. 3, pp. 76-81.</P><P><FONT COLOR="#660000">&#183;</FONT>&nbsp;David Patterson. "From Exile to Affirmation: The Poetry of Joseph Brodsky," Studies in 20th Century Literature, Summer 1993, vol. 17 (2), pp. 365-83.</P><P><FONT COLOR="#660000">&#183;</FONT>&nbsp;Dennis Ryan. "Joseph Brodsky and the Fictions of Poetry, Including Vers Libre," Lituanus, Summer 1993, vol. 39 (2), pp. 70-77.</P><P><FONT COLOR="#660000">&#183;</FONT>&nbsp;David Bethea. "Joseph Brodsky and the American Seashore Poem: Lowell, Mandelstam and Cape Cod," Harvard Review, Spring 1994, vol. 6, pp. 115-122.</P><P><FONT COLOR="#660000">&#183;</FONT>&nbsp;Wlad Godzich. "Brodsky and the Grounding of Poetry," The Georgia Review, Spring 1995, vol. 49 (1), pp. 195-215.</P><P><FONT COLOR="#660000">&#183;</FONT>&nbsp;Richard Kostelanetz. "Joseph Brodsky and the Myth of Privileged Background," Talisman: A Journal of Contemporary Poetry and Poetics, Fall 1996, vol. 16, pp. 238-241.</P><FORM ACTION="http://www.infography.com/Action.cgi" METHOD="post"><INPUT TYPE="hidden" NAME="-Database" VALUE="contentsearch"><INPUT TYPE="hidden" NAME="-Layout" VALUE="web"><INPUT TYPE="hidden" NAME="-Response" VALUE="listing.cgi"><INPUT TYPE="hidden" NAME="-NoResultsError" VALUE="noresults.cgi"><INPUT TYP